Sentencas: In the first part of this two-paper series, we presented a numerical model of the impedance behaviour of a solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) aimed at simulating the change in the impedance spectrum induced by contact degradation at the interconnect-electrode, and at the electrode-electrolyte interfaces.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: The purpose of that investigation was to develop a non-invasive diagnostic technique to identify degradation modes in situ.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: In the present paper, we appraise the predictive capabilities of the proposed method in terms of its robustness to uncertainties in the input parameters, many of which are very difficult to measure independently.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: We applied this technique to the degradation modes simulated in Part I, in addition to anode sulfur poisoning.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: Electrode delamination showed the highest robustness to input parameter variations, followed by interconnect oxidation and interconnect detachment.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: The most sensitive degradation mode was sulfur poisoning, due to strong parameter interactions.
Titulo: Short stack modeling of degradation in solid oxide fuel cells - Part II. Sensitivity and interaction analysis

Sentencas: In addition, we simulate several simultaneous two-degradation-mode scenarios, assessing the method's capabilities and limitations for the prediction of electrochemical behaviour of SOFC's undergoing multiple simultaneous degradation modes.
